react-native-component-initialization-st:
Hi @zhongwuzw I made some investigation and I don't think that this is the right fix.

The problem with this is that, after recycle, the default value for the UISwitch is `true`. While the oldProp is holding a value of `false`. The new prop is `false`, so the value is not set.

I think that the right fix should be applied in the `updateProps:` function, like this:

```diff
-  if (oldSwitchProps.value != newSwitchProps.value) {
+  if (!_isInitialValueSet || oldSwitchProps.value != newSwitchProps.value) {
    BOOL shouldAnimate = _isInitialValueSet == YES;
    [_switchView setOn:newSwitchProps.value animated:shouldAnimate];
  }
```
This will force ReactNative to set the initial value on the switch in the first rendering, which is the correct behavior, because that will be the first rendering for the recycled component.

